<div id="review_3230113456" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3230113456" />
    <a title="Eric Hollen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21843537-eric-hollen"><img alt="Eric Hollen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500384014p2/21843537.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3230113456?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric Hollen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric Hollen" href="/user/show/21843537-eric-hollen">Eric Hollen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/22436684-the-rise-of-theodore-roosevelt">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3230113456" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16135865309423818605">&quot;Mistah SPEEK-AH! Mistah SPEE-KAH!&quot;<br/><br/>A very well-written and engaging biography. Roosevelt, pre-presidency, was a man of boundless energy and ambition. A cross between his privileged, millionaire, Harvard-educated East society, and his rugged, colloquial, rancher Western crowd, Roosevelt embodied his idea of what he thought it meant to be American. While at times the narrative felt like it was written by an old white dude (some cringeworthy moments with women and Native Americans), Morris does a f</span>
  <span id="freeText16135865309423818605" style="display:none">"Mistah SPEEK-AH! Mistah SPEE-KAH!"<br /><br />A very well-written and engaging biography. Roosevelt, pre-presidency, was a man of boundless energy and ambition. A cross between his privileged, millionaire, Harvard-educated East society, and his rugged, colloquial, rancher Western crowd, Roosevelt embodied his idea of what he thought it meant to be American. While at times the narrative felt like it was written by an old white dude (some cringeworthy moments with women and Native Americans), Morris does a fine job of documenting the life of a man who has worn "many hats." I think the only thing I wanted to know more about was Roosevelt the husband, the family man. For someone who embodies a lot of core WASP values, I was pretty surprised we didn't see more about Roosevelt the husband, Roosevelt the father. At 800 pages the book's already pretty long, but it seemed more like Morris wanted to focus on the political and historical. Other than that, it was a fine read and I'm looking forward to the next two. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16135865309423818605" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


