  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_451919541" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/451919541" />
    <a title="Markus Molina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10102477-markus-molina"><img alt="Markus Molina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1565100176p2/10102477.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/451919541?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Markus Molina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Markus Molina" href="/user/show/10102477-markus-molina">Markus Molina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780698107830" href="/book/show/286268.The_Rise_of_Theodore_Roosevelt">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer451919541" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17243733704946393430"> Firstly, I&apos;d like to preface this review by stating, I&apos;m really not into politics much at all and find it boring for the most part, so I can imagine more political folk enjoying this book a lot more than I did. I decided to pick up this review after my professor was discussing him in class with such pep and enthusiasm, I was compelled to read up on him.<br/><br/>Roosevelt is probably the most interesting man to ever run for office, in my opinion. And this book brought him to life waaay better than my pro</span>
  <span id="freeText17243733704946393430" style="display:none"> Firstly, I'd like to preface this review by stating, I'm really not into politics much at all and find it boring for the most part, so I can imagine more political folk enjoying this book a lot more than I did. I decided to pick up this review after my professor was discussing him in class with such pep and enthusiasm, I was compelled to read up on him.<br /><br />Roosevelt is probably the most interesting man to ever run for office, in my opinion. And this book brought him to life waaay better than my professor did. Roosevelt is unreal. He reminds me of the tall tales I'd hear as a kid, but honestly he is more manly than 4 Paul Bunyans in my mind. His heroics are jaw-dropping. From being the young gun in congress, to standing face to face and preparing to fight against assailing native americans out for his head, to swimming with sharks, reading 3 pages a minute and 2 books a day, capturing thieves who stole his boat by building a boat with his bare hands and chasing them way farther than he should have, patrolling the streets at 3 in the morning, cleaning up the crooked NY cops and politicians like some sort of super hero, and at 40 years old making due of his promise that he'd fight for america when the time came. So, he goes and starts his rough riders, riding horses like maniacs into cuba, for the Spanish/American war. His own soldiers couldn't even believe his heroics, from his jumping with joy when snipers starting reigning down on his squad, and staying on his horse to fight back against them. The dude was nuts! And he did all these things while being one of most important politician of all time AND while writing a ton of books. Oh yeah, then he goes and becomes the youngest president of all time. <br /><br />The man was incredible, and for that, this book is worth reading. <br /><br />The things I didn't like about this book, like I said, were a lot of the really political stuff was very dry for me. I know, you're thinking, "why would you read about a politician if you weren't interested in politics?" I wanted to educate myself, is that so strange? <br /><br />Hahahhaar, anywho,<br />I love Teddy, I think most people would.<br /><br />Check out this book if you're interested.<br />I'm feeling patriotic!</span>
  <a data-text-id="17243733704946393430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


